function ArticleModal({ isOpen, onClose }) {
  if (!isOpen) return null;
  
  return (
    <div style={{ position: "fixed", inset: 0, background: "rgba(0,0,0,0.8)", backdropFilter: "blur(8px)", zIndex: 200, display: "flex", alignItems: "flex-start", justifyContent: "center", padding: 24, overflowY: "auto" }}>
      <div style={{ background: colors.bgWhite, borderRadius: 16, maxWidth: 680, width: "100%", border: `1px solid ${colors.border}`, position: "relative", margin: "48px 0" }}>
        <button onClick={onClose} style={{ position: "fixed", top: 24, right: 24, padding: 12, background: colors.bgWhite, border: `1px solid ${colors.border}`, borderRadius: 8, cursor: "pointer", zIndex: 210 }}><X size={20} style={{ color: colors.textMuted }} /></button>
        
        <div style={{ padding: "64px 48px" }}>
          <div style={{ marginBottom: 32 }}>
            <span style={{ fontFamily: fonts.mono, fontSize: 11, color: colors.purple, letterSpacing: "0.1em", textTransform: "uppercase" }}>Why We Built Cirth</span>
            <h1 style={{ fontFamily: fonts.display, fontSize: 36, fontWeight: 800, color: colors.text, marginTop: 12, lineHeight: 1.2 }}>The Meaning Problem</h1>
            <p style={{ fontFamily: fonts.body, fontSize: 14, color: colors.textMuted, marginTop: 12 }}>By Ty Linegar</p>
          </div>
          
          <div style={{ fontFamily: fonts.body, fontSize: 17, color: colors.text, lineHeight: 1.8 }}>
            <p style={{ marginBottom: 24 }}>I've spent years working on national brand campaigns. Big brands, real budgets, the kind of work that looks impressive in a portfolio. And the job, if I'm honest about it, was always the same: find the meaning.</p>
            
            <p style={{ marginBottom: 24 }}>The problem is that for most consumer products, there isn't any.</p>
            
            <p style={{ marginBottom: 24 }}>Hair product. Soda. Insurance... A drop in an ocean of competitors who do it just as well for roughly the same price. So our job is to manufacture meaning. Build mythology. Attach the product to identity  to aspiration, to belonging. You make people feel like buying this particular thing says something about who they are.</p>
            
            <p style={{ marginBottom: 24 }}>It works. That's the craft, and there's real skill in it. But there's also a hollow center to the whole enterprise that you learn to stop noticing. You're building on nothing. The brand is the product because there's no other differentiation. The story you're telling isn't a story about anything real.</p>
            
            <p style={{ marginBottom: 24 }}>I don't think this is evil. It's just the logic of consumer markets. When the thing itself doesn't matter much, the narrative has to do all the work.</p>
            
            <p style={{ marginBottom: 48 }}>But it's exhausting. And after enough years, you start to wonder what it would feel like to tell a story that was already true.</p>
            
            <div style={{ width: 48, height: 2, background: colors.purple, marginBottom: 48 }} />
            
            <p style={{ marginBottom: 24 }}>There's a different economy emerging, and a lot of it runs through El Segundo.</p>
            
            <p style={{ marginBottom: 24 }}>Not the El Segundo of aerospace's old guard, though that's part of the DNA. Something newer. The SpaceX diaspora. Defense tech startups. Companies building power systems, satellites, autonomous platforms, infrastructure that matters. Hard tech.</p>
            
            <p style={{ marginBottom: 24 }}>These founders are a different species. They're not optimizing for the next funding round or trying to capture attention in a crowded market. They're building things because they believe those things need to exist. For national security. For energy independence. For the kind of future where humanity becomes more capable rather than just more connected.</p>
            
            <p style={{ marginBottom: 24 }}>The stakes are different. The buyers are different. A defense procurement officer evaluates on substance. Whether your system works, whether your team can deliver, whether you understand their constraints. But they're also human. They chose their career for a reason. They believe in something. Campaigns should make them feel the weight of what a founder has built and connect them to the mission.</p>
            
            <p style={{ marginBottom: 48 }}>And the founders themselves are serious in a way that's become rare. Many are Faustian idealists who have dedicated their souls to advancing civilization. Many of them left comfortable careers because they thought something important wasn't getting built.</p>
            
            <div style={{ width: 48, height: 2, background: colors.purple, marginBottom: 48 }} />
            
            <p style={{ marginBottom: 24 }}>Here's the mismatch: traditional agencies are optimized for consumer brands.</p>
            
            <p style={{ marginBottom: 24 }}>Their playbooks, their instincts, their talent pipelines are all built for a world where the job is manufacturing meaning. Creating desire. Making people feel something about products that don't inherently matter.</p>
            
            <p style={{ marginBottom: 24 }}>Bring that machinery to hard tech and it doesn't just underperform. It actively damages.</p>
            
            <p style={{ marginBottom: 24 }}>The slick campaign that would crush it for a DTC brand reads as unserious to a defense buyer. The brand voice that sounds "authentic" in consumer markets sounds performative and cringe to engineers. The agency's instinct to lead with emotion over substance is exactly backwards for an audience that needs to trust the specs before they'll trust the story.</p>
            
            <p style={{ marginBottom: 48 }}>When a founder who is solving nuclear waste storage or building better missile defense systems encounters an agency that wants to spend weeks deconstructing "brand purpose", there's a disconnect that can't be bridged by a better pitch deck.</p>
            
            <div style={{ width: 48, height: 2, background: colors.purple, marginBottom: 48 }} />
            
            <p style={{ marginBottom: 24 }}>What's driving me though isn't just an opportunity to correct what agencies get wrong, it's the sense of the divine possible when you get it right. Amplifying an undeniable force through story and content is an incredibly fulfilling promise.</p>
            
            <p style={{ marginBottom: 24 }}>When I look at this industry, I see a company cloud seeding to transform barren desert wastelands into thriving green landscapes. Teams building the infrastructure for humanity to reach other worlds. Startups engineering power systems that could reshape civilization. Otherworldly defense technology protecting the people and values that make any of this possible.</p>
            
            <p style={{ marginBottom: 24 }}>This isn't just technically impressive. It's beautiful. There's genuine cinematic weight to what's being built. The raw material is better than anything a consumer brand could dream of.</p>
            
            <p style={{ marginBottom: 48 }}>The problem with traditional agencies isn't that they lack craft and creativity. It's that their craft and creativity is in service of nothing. When you're selling shampoo, you have to manufacture feeling from a void. Hard tech is the inverse. The feeling is earned. The story is already true. Which means the creative work stops being manipulation and becomes finally worthy of itself, as genuine meaning given form.</p>
            
            <div style={{ width: 48, height: 2, background: colors.purple, marginBottom: 48 }} />
            
            <p style={{ marginBottom: 24 }}>This IS a new frontier, and we are watching the early innings of something civilizationally significant. A generation of builders focused on energy, defense, space, infrastructure  the kind of work that actually moves the needle on what humanity is capable of.</p>
            
            <p style={{ marginBottom: 24 }}>This movement deserves storytelling that takes it seriously. Not the hollow machinery of consumer marketing. Not performance. Not manufactured meaning.</p>
            
            <p style={{ marginBottom: 24 }}>Something that matches the ambition of what's being built. That captures the weight of it. That makes people feel what's true.</p>
            
            <p style={{ fontWeight: 600, color: colors.purple }}>The substance is finally worthy of the craft. That's what Cirth Studio is built for.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}

